	<transcript sound="sound1"><![CDATA[We now know what a food hazard is-anything that has the potential to cause harm to the consumer.<br/><br/>There are four types of hazard:<br /><li>(Micro) biological - such as bacteria, viruses, moulds and parasites;</li><br /><li>Physical - such as glass, screws, drawing pins, and stones;</li><br /><li>Chemical - such as insecticides and cleaning agents;</li><br /><li>Allergenic - food that can cause allergic reactions, such as peanuts and sesame seeds.</li><br /><br />Click on the icon to find out more about your responsibilities as a food handler. When you have finished, click 'Next' to continue.]]></transcript>
	
	<transcript sound="sound2"><![CDATA[Apart from knowing the types of hazards and how to control them, it is also important to know your company’s reporting procedures, for example, if there is a glass breakage or you see a rodent.<br /><br />Your responsibility is:<li>To learn about food safety and keep your knowledge up-to-date;</li><li>To control potential hazards and practice good food safety;</li><li>To protect your customers.</li>]]></transcript>

